GitHub – Quick Start Guide

This short guide explains how to:
- create a GitHub account
- upload files to a repository
- manage files using GitHub’s web interface

GitHub is an online platform used to:
- store code and files
- track changes over time
- collaborate with other people

A repository is an online folder that contains your project files

1. Creating a GitHub Account

Go to -> https://github.com
Click Sign up
Enter:
- a username
- an email address
- a password
Confirm your email address
The free plan is sufficient

2. Accessing a Repository

A public repository can be viewed by anyone
To modify files, you must be the owner, or be added as a collaborator

To access a repository:
Log in to GitHub
Open the repository link in your browser

3. Uploading Files

a. Adding new files
Open the repository
Click Add file → Upload files
Drag and drop files (or select them from your computer)
Write a short message (e.g. “Add initial scripts”)
Click Commit changes

b. Creating folders
Folders are created automatically when you upload files inside them

4. Editing an Existing File

Open the file in the repository
Click the Edit icon
Modify the content
Write a short description of the change
Click Commit changes
GitHub keeps a full history of all changes.

6. Downloading Files

a. Download a single file
Open the file → click Download

b. Download the entire repository
Click Code → Download ZIP

7. Contributing Without Direct Access

If you do not have write permission:
Click Fork
Make changes in your own copy
Open a Pull Request
The repository owner reviews and decides whether to accept it

8. What you should NOT upload

- Passwords
- API tokens
- Private keys
- Real .env files
- Sensitive or personal data

Public repositories are visible to everyone.

9. Basic Best Practices

Use clear and descriptive file names
Write short but meaningful commit messages
Avoid uploading very large files
Always read the README.md

10. Useful Resources

GitHub Documentation -> https://docs.github.com
GitHub Hello World -> https://docs.github.com/get-started/quickstart
